EDF 5400 ADHD Labs: Summary of SPSS commands used.

SPSS Command Summary

A cheat sheet for all SPSS commands used in EDF 5400.

Note that under Windows certain letters in menu items are underlined. (SPSS follows this convention in the Windows version.) These can be used to select menu items using the keyboard. Press and hold the Alt key and press the key corresponding to the menu (.e.g, F for File, V for view, I for Insert, T for Transform, G for Graphs, and A for Analyze). The menu should then flop down, and then you can select the item by pressing its underlined letter. If that menu has submenus, you might need to press more letters.

One other interesting detail about the interface is that if a menu item ends in three dots (...) that means it will open up a dialog allowing you to specify details (or cancel).

Getting Data Into SPSS

Input and Output

  • File > Open > Data [ALT+F O A]

Can both load SPSS .sav files and other data formats (.txt, .csv, .xls)

  • File > Export… [ALT+F E]

Save output in Word, PDF, RTF formats.

You can select those parts of the output you want to export in the right hand side of the output viewer window.

  • View > Variables [Control+T]

Switch between data and meta-data (variable list) views. This can also be done using the tabs at the bottom of the window. On MacOS, the shortcut is [CMD+T] instead of control.

Annotation

These three commands can be used to add comments and notes to your SPSS output. Use these: the notes are critical for remembering what you did at a later time.

  • Insert > New Title [Alt+I T]

  • Insert > New Text [Alt+I X]

  • Insert > New Page Title [Alt+I A]

Data Manipulation

These commands allow the analyst to recode categorical variables, and combine or rescale other varaibles.

  • Transform > Compute Variable…* [ALT+T C]

Creates new variable according to a formula or rule

  • Transform > Automatic Recode… [ALT+T A]

Recodes strings as numbers (for nominal and ordinal data)

  • Data > Select Cases… [ALT+D S]

Can be used to remove outliers and look at data subsets. Don’t forget to turn it off when you are done!

Exploratory Data Analysis

Text Summaries

  • Analyze > De scriptive Statistics > Descriptive… [Alt+A E D]

Mean, Std., and other basic stats

  • Analyze > De scriptive Statistics > Frequencies… [ALT+A E F]

More basic stats, plus frequency table (often not needed).

Graphical Displays

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Box plot… [ALT+G L X]

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Scatter/Dot… [ALT+ G L S]

Note this can be used for one variable at a time (dot plot), two variables (scatterplot) or three or more variables (scatterplot matrix).

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Histogram… [ALT+G L I]

Basic exploratory graphics tools

Distributional Shape

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Histogram… [ALT+G L I]

Can add normal (or other distribution) reference curve

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Box plot… [ALT+G L X]

  • Analyze > Descriptive Statistics > Q-Q Plots… [ALT+A E Q]

This compares quantiles of observed distribution to quantiles of a reference distribution (usually normal). Straight line indicates good fit.

(This is a useful tool for evaluating model fit, which there is not quite enough time to cover in EDF5400. There is an optional lecture on the canvas site.

Correlation and Regression

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Scatter/Dot… [ALT+G L S]

  • Analyze > Correlate > Bivariate… [ALT+A C B]

  • Analyze > Regression > Linear… [ALT+A R L]

Comparing Groups

Summary Statistics and Graphs

  • Analyze > Compare Means > Means… [ALT+A M M]

Tables by mean and variance

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Boxplot… [ALT+G L X]

Really good for comparing groups

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Histogram… [ALT+G L I]

Use “Panel by rows” to compare groups

Compare Groups: Tests

  • Analyze > Compare Means > Independent-Sample T-Test… [ALT+A M T]

Compare two groups

  • Analyze > Compare Means > One Sample T Test… [ALT+A M S]

Compare group to 0 or historic value

  • Analyze > Com pare Means > Paired-Samples T Test… [ALT+A M P]

Comparison pairs of matched individuals (often before/after comparisons)

Effect size Calculators

These were necessary in older versions of SPSS which did not have Cohen’s \(d\) as part of the output. * effectSize_d.xls (Excel format) * Effect Size Web Gadget

Categorical Data

One-variable tests

  • Analyze > De scriptive Statistics > Frequencies… [ALT+A D F]

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Bar… [ALT+G L B]

  • Graphs > Legacy Dialogs > Pie… [ALT+G L E]

  • Analyze > Nonparametric Tests > Legacy Dialogs > Chi-square… [ALT+A N L C]

Compares observed counts to reference distribution (usually uniform). One-way chisquare test.

2-way tests (Crosstabs)

  • Analyze > Descriptive Statistics > Crosstabs… [ALT+A D C]

Chi-square test of independence (also other tests, not used in EDF 5400 but useful in other contexts)

Usually will want to select row or column percentages, but not both.
